    "session-2026-03-23": {
      "id": "session-2026-03-23",
      "name": "Sunday, March 22, 2026 — 11:00 PM",
      "content": "<p><strong>Proactive outline updates this session:</strong></p><p></p><ul><li><p>Added Section 11 (App Store Compliance) to Bootstrap Plan — 7 detail nodes + TODO checklist from Development outline audit</p></li><li><p>Added BOOTSTRAP CHECKLIST (CL) with 8 milestone sections and pre-checked completed items</p></li><li><p>Checked off \"Apple Developer Program\" in CL.1 (user confirmed renewal)</p></li><li><p>Checked off \"AI Consent Dialog\" and \"Privacy Policy\" in CL.7 (implemented this session)</p></li><li><p>Fixed CL.1 checkboxes overwritten by app — converted Unicode checkmarks to interactive TipTap TaskList format</p></li><li><p>Added 5-second external modification polling to prevent app from overwriting Claude's outline edits</p></li><li><p>Updated Development outline 10.1.2 — replaced broken HTML table with bulleted list</p></li><li><p>Added level 3 prefixes (10.1.1–10.1.7) to all Apple compliance child nodes</p></li></ul><p></p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "session-actions-log",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": "1.1.1"
    },
    "session-2026-03-23b": {
      "id": "session-2026-03-23b",
      "name": "Sunday, March 23, 2026 — 2:30 AM (continued)",
      "content": "<p><strong>Proactive updates this session:</strong></p><p></p><ul><li><p>Added search filter toggles (Names/Content) to outline search bar</p></li><li><p>Added two-step AI consent decline flow — warning screen lists all features that will be disabled before confirming</p></li><li><p>Disabled auto-open DevTools in Electron dev mode for cleaner testing</p></li><li><p>Fixed Generate Content server action parameter mismatch</p></li><li><p>Fixed Generate AI Diagram env var (GOOGLE_API_KEY → GEMINI_API_KEY)</p></li><li><p>Added external modification polling (5-second interval) to prevent app from overwriting Claude's outline edits</p></li><li><p>Added Fn key pass-through in Electron for macOS dictation</p></li><li><p>Updated documentation: initial-guide, help-chat context, API route for AI consent feature</p></li><li><p>Outline sweep: updated How It Works (AI consent system, external mod detection, search filters), Killer Features (5 new entries), Current Features (search filters, AI consent, privacy policy), Testing (3 new manual test procedures), Legal &amp; Compliance (privacy policy + AI consent status → IMPLEMENTED)</p></li></ul>",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isExpanded": true,
      "prefix": "1.1.2"
    },
    "session-2026-03-27": {
      "id": "session-2026-03-27",
      "name": "Thursday, March 27, 2026",
      "content": "<p><strong>Proactive updates this session:</strong></p><ul><li><p>Changed all purple/violet icon colors to emerald green for dark mode readability</p></li><li><p>Added light/dark mode theme toggle in Settings (using next-themes)</p></li><li><p>Added dark mode variants to all icon colors across every component</p></li><li><p>Replaced dark blue icons with sky blue for better contrast</p></li><li><p>Fixed search filter toggle buttons — now go dim immediately on click</p></li><li><p>Swapped search filter icons (outline icon for names, T for content)</p></li><li><p>Checked availability of 53 candidate product names — 37 taken, 16 available</p></li><li><p>Added Available/Taken child nodes to Killer Features outline</p></li><li><p>Added no-code-output rule to top of CLAUDE.md for stronger enforcement</p></li></ul>",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isExpanded": true,
      "prefix": "1.1.3"
    },
    "session-2026-04-02": {
      "id": "session-2026-04-02",
      "name": "Wednesday, April 2–3, 2026",
      "content": "<p><strong>Proactive updates this session:</strong></p><ul><li><p>Removed depth indicator lines and chapter border indicators from outline tree for cleaner look</p></li><li><p>Brightened dark mode primary color (iOS blue → brighter sky blue) for better readability</p></li><li><p>Comprehensive color scan — fixed 13 visibility issues across all components for both light/dark modes</p></li><li><p>Added diagram type selector to Generate Content dropdown (9 types including Auto)</p></li><li><p>Fixed green button hover disappearing in light mode</p></li><li><p>Implemented cascading Escape key — dismisses search, highlights, AI ops, multi-select, deselect in priority order</p></li><li><p>Added Clear button (eraser icon) to search bar for clearing highlights</p></li><li><p>Fixed flushSync crash in outline lazy loading</p></li><li><p>Added ITSAppUsesNonExemptEncryption flag to Info.plist</p></li><li><p>TestFlight: uploaded macOS build, configured App Store Connect compliance, deployed to iMac via TestFlight</p></li></ul><p></p>",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isExpanded": true,
      "prefix": "1.1.4"
    },
    "24012bb0-25b8-4c07-ad1c-cec65f144740": {
      "id": "24012bb0-25b8-4c07-ad1c-cec65f144740",
      "name": "Enterprise API Agreements — Action Plan",
      "parentId": "root-bootstrap",
      "childrenIds": [
        "273ca244-01cf-47c3-a1a7-6f86da438b59",
        "cba17c9c-9334-425a-b282-da1bf38c4b41",
        "41367a2d-f980-443e-b443-765cb2662f88",
        "6ea7a974-c28c-4a86-9223-6a9540e8ad4d",
        "84fcac3d-536e-44bc-a786-e424d22568d0"
      ],
      "type": "chapter",
      "content": "<p><strong>Goal:</strong> Negotiate volume API discounts with major LLM providers so Premium subscribers get AI included in their subscription without needing their own API keys. The discount we negotiate is our profit margin.</p><p><strong>Business model:</strong> Free users bring their own keys (zero cost to us). Premium users ($9.99/month) get AI bundled — we pay ~$0.60-2.40/month per user in API costs, keeping $7.59-9.39 as margin.</p><p><strong>Priority order:</strong> Google Gemini first (already our default), then OpenAI, Anthropic, Groq. Start applications immediately — these take weeks to process.</p>",
      "prefix": "15"
    },
    "273ca244-01cf-47c3-a1a7-6f86da438b59": {
      "id": "273ca244-01cf-47c3-a1a7-6f86da438b59",
      "name": "1. Google Gemini (Start Here)",
      "parentId": "24012bb0-25b8-4c07-ad1c-cec65f144740",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Why first:</strong> Gemini is already our default AI provider. Getting volume pricing here covers the majority of API calls.</p><h3>Step 1: Apply to Google Cloud Partner Program</h3><ol><li><p>Go to <strong>cloud.google.com/partners</strong></p></li><li><p>Click \"Become a Partner\" or \"Apply Now\"</p></li><li><p>Select: Technology Partner / ISV (Independent Software Vendor)</p></li><li><p>Company name: SecondBrainWare (or your legal entity name)</p></li><li><p>Description: \"SecondBrainWare is an AI-powered personal knowledge management platform. We use the Gemini API for text generation, multimodal vision (image analysis), research synthesis, and conversational knowledge search. Our users are researchers, professionals, and lifelong learners. We deploy via web (Vercel), macOS (Electron), and iOS (Capacitor).\"</p></li><li><p>Requested product: Gemini API / Generative AI</p></li><li><p>Expected volume: Start with estimated monthly API spend, scale projections</p></li></ol><h3>Step 2: Apply to Google Cloud Startup Program</h3><ol><li><p>Go to <strong>cloud.google.com/startup</strong></p></li><li><p>Apply for credits (typically $2,000-$100,000 depending on stage)</p></li><li><p>This gives you free API usage while the partner agreement processes</p></li><li><p>Use the same description as above</p></li></ol><h3>What to expect:</h3><ul><li><p>Partner program: 2-4 weeks to process. May involve a technical review call.</p></li><li><p>Startup program: 1-2 weeks. Usually approved quickly for early-stage companies.</p></li><li><p>Volume discounts typically 20-40% off retail Gemini API pricing.</p></li></ul><p><strong>Status:</strong> Submitted 2026-04-XX (prior session — Google Cloud Partner Program + Startup Program). Awaiting response.</p>",
      "prefix": "15.1"
    },
    "cba17c9c-9334-425a-b282-da1bf38c4b41": {
      "id": "cba17c9c-9334-425a-b282-da1bf38c4b41",
      "name": "2. OpenAI",
      "parentId": "24012bb0-25b8-4c07-ad1c-cec65f144740",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Why:</strong> Currently used for podcast TTS only. Enterprise agreement would also let us offer GPT-4o as a text generation option in Premium tier.</p><h3>Steps:</h3><ol><li><p>Go to <strong>openai.com/contact-sales</strong></p></li><li><p>Fill out the enterprise inquiry form</p></li><li><p>Use case: \"SecondBrainWare embeds OpenAI APIs for text-to-speech podcast generation and optionally GPT-4o for text generation. We offer these as bundled features in a SaaS subscription.\"</p></li><li><p>Ask specifically about: ISV/reseller program, volume discount pricing, committed-use agreements</p></li><li><p>Expected usage: Start with TTS volume estimates, project text generation adoption</p></li></ol><h3>What to expect:</h3><ul><li><p>2-4 weeks for initial response</p></li><li><p>They'll want to understand your projected API spend</p></li><li><p>Enterprise agreements typically require minimum monthly commitment</p></li></ul><p><strong>Status:</strong> Submitted 2026-05-06. OpenAI Sales contact form. Org ID org-MAMIO0NAUtjxVQuxtheGF0H2 ($8.56 starter credit). Awaiting response.</p>",
      "prefix": "15.2"
    },
    "41367a2d-f980-443e-b443-765cb2662f88": {
      "id": "41367a2d-f980-443e-b443-765cb2662f88",
      "name": "3. Anthropic Claude",
      "parentId": "24012bb0-25b8-4c07-ad1c-cec65f144740",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Why:</strong> Claude excels at long-form reasoning and research synthesis — a perfect fit for Knowledge Chat and the Second Brain search feature. Position as the premium AI option.</p>\n\n<h3>Steps:</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Go to <strong>anthropic.com/contact-sales</strong></li>\n<li>Select \"Building with the API\" or ISV option</li>\n<li>Description: \"SecondBrainWare is a knowledge management platform. We want to offer Claude as a premium AI option for research synthesis, long-form reasoning, and conversational knowledge base queries. Users accumulate knowledge in a 'Second Brain' and query it with natural language.\"</li>\n<li>Ask about: Volume pricing, ISV/partner program, committed-use discounts</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h3>What to expect:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Anthropic is selective but interested in production use cases</li>\n<li>Emphasize the research/knowledge management angle — it's a strong fit for Claude's strengths</li>\n<li>Expect 2-6 weeks for response</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Status:</strong> Submitted 2026-05-08 via anthropic.com/contact-sales using business email howard@2ndbrainware.com. Awaiting response.</p>",
      "prefix": "15.3"
    },
    "6ea7a974-c28c-4a86-9223-6a9540e8ad4d": {
      "id": "6ea7a974-c28c-4a86-9223-6a9540e8ad4d",
      "name": "4. Groq",
      "parentId": "24012bb0-25b8-4c07-ad1c-cec65f144740",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Why:</strong> Extremely fast inference (sub-second responses). Use as the speed-optimized option for quick queries — Knowledge Chat quick mode, short content generation, real-time suggestions.</p>\n\n<h3>Steps:</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Check <strong>groq.com/partners</strong> or look for partner info in <strong>console.groq.com</strong></li>\n<li>Apply as a startup/ISV partner</li>\n<li>Description: \"SecondBrainWare would use Groq for fast inference on time-sensitive queries — knowledge base search, quick content suggestions, and real-time AI features where latency matters.\"</li>\n<li>Ask about startup credits and volume pricing</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h3>What to expect:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Groq has generous free tier and startup programs</li>\n<li>They're actively seeking production use cases to showcase their speed advantage</li>\n<li>May get significant free credits to start</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Status:</strong> Submitted 2026-05-08 via Groq Enterprise Inquiry form. Selected models: llama-3.3-70b-versatile, llama-3.1-8b-instant, llama-4-scout, whisper-large-v3-turbo, compound-mini. Awaiting response.</p>",
      "prefix": "15.4"
    },
    "84fcac3d-536e-44bc-a786-e424d22568d0": {
      "id": "84fcac3d-536e-44bc-a786-e424d22568d0",
      "name": "5. Technical Integration (Claude Code handles this)",
      "parentId": "24012bb0-25b8-4c07-ad1c-cec65f144740",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Once at least one agreement is signed, I'll build:</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Managed API proxy</strong> — Server route that authenticates user subscription tier and routes AI calls through our enterprise keys</li>\n<li><strong>Usage tracking</strong> — Per-user API call counting for billing and quota management</li>\n<li><strong>Smart routing</strong> — Automatically pick the best provider per task (Gemini for vision, Claude for reasoning, Groq for speed)</li>\n<li><strong>Subscription tier gating</strong> — Free users → must bring own key. Premium users → AI calls go through our proxy automatically.</li>\n<li><strong>Fallback chain</strong> — If one provider is down or rate-limited, automatically try the next</li>\n</ol>\n<p>No action needed from Howard on this — I'll implement it when the first enterprise key is available.</p>",
      "prefix": "15.5"
    },
    "session-2026-05-08": {
      "id": "session-2026-05-08",
      "name": "Friday, May 8, 2026",
      "parentId": "session-actions-log",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Enterprise API Applications — Final Push:</strong></p><ul><li><p>Submitted Anthropic Claude enterprise inquiry via anthropic.com/contact-sales (business email howard@2ndbrainware.com — gmail blocked). Pitched Claude as premium AI tier for research synthesis and Second Brain reasoning.</p></li><li><p>Submitted Groq enterprise inquiry via groq.com Enterprise Plan form. Pitched Groq as speed-optimized provider for time-sensitive features (Knowledge Chat quick mode, voice transcription via Whisper, real-time suggestions). Selected 5 models: llama-3.3-70b-versatile, llama-3.1-8b-instant, llama-4-scout, whisper-large-v3-turbo, compound-mini.</p></li></ul><p><strong>Status of all 4 enterprise applications:</strong> ALL SUBMITTED ✓ (Google ✓ Apr, OpenAI ✓ May 6, Anthropic ✓ May 8, Groq ✓ May 8). Now waiting on responses (typical timeline: 1–4 weeks).</p><p><strong>iOS TestFlight (#27):</strong> Web build + iOS sync complete. Xcode project opened. Archive + upload paused — user is on slow internet, will resume when at office.</p><p><strong>Memory updates:</strong> Saved business email (howard@2ndbrainware.com) as reference memory for future enterprise forms.</p>",
      "isExpanded": true,
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "unrealized-todo-20260513": {
      "id": "unrealized-todo-20260513",
      "name": "Unrealized Features TODO (2026-05-13)",
      "parentId": "root-bootstrap",
      "childrenIds": [
        "unrealized-livebooks",
        "unrealized-platform-gaps",
        "unrealized-mcp",
        "unrealized-group",
        "unrealized-external-deps"
      ],
      "type": "chapter",
      "content": "<p>Consolidated list of unrealized features that are not yet on the existing milestone checklists or compliance TODO. Compiled 2026-05-13 by cross-referencing the Bootstrap Plan against the Killer Features, MCP Plan, Group, and Rosetta Stone outlines plus the live codebase. Items already tracked elsewhere (Quick Capture, Second Brain Dashboard, Smart Auto-Tagging — all shipped; iOS TestFlight upload — already noted in Session Log; 4 enterprise API agreements — already in Section 15; subscription billing infrastructure — already in M3) were intentionally omitted to avoid duplicate tracking.</p>",
      "prefix": "16"
    },
    "unrealized-livebooks": {
      "id": "unrealized-livebooks",
      "name": "LIVE BOOKS — New Product Surface",
      "parentId": "unrealized-todo-20260513",
      "childrenIds": [
        "livebooks-sharing-roadmap-20260515"
      ],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Status:</strong> Pricing decided. All 6 design questions CLOSED &mdash; decided 2026-05-15. Implementation not started (see task #2).</p><p></p><p><strong>Pricing (decided):</strong></p><ul><li><p>BYOK (Bring Your Own Key) required</p></li><li><p>$9.99/month flat fee on top of BYOK</p></li></ul><p></p><p><strong>Design Decisions (closed 2026-05-15):</strong></p><p><strong>Feature concept:</strong> Take any outline and refresh its content against the latest information on the internet so static documents don't go stale. Manual and user-controlled. Local-first — v1 has NO dependency on the unbuilt collaboration feature.</p><ul><li><p><strong>Q1 — Refresh Scope — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> Trigger is MANUAL ONLY, invoked by the author or reader; no scheduled or automatic refresh in v1. A refresh dialog is shown; the default scope is the currently selected node PLUS all of its descendants, so selecting the root node refreshes the entire outline. Frequency is manual invocation only to start — no caps and no automation.</p></li><li><p><strong>Q2 — Diff / Review Step — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> By default, always: preview → user approves → then implemented. If the change is not accepted it is rejected and nothing is altered. Auto-apply is NEVER the default; it is an explicit opt-in the user must deliberately select to relinquish control for that specific refresh, and it covers the selected node plus its descendants.</p></li><li><p><strong>Q3 — Author vs Reader Versions — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> v1 is a personal fork — a reader's refresh creates their own copy and the author's canonical version is never touched by a reader. This is satisfied for free by the existing file export/import model (no sharing infrastructure needed; LIVE BOOKS v1 has no dependency on the unbuilt collaboration feature, task #12). Deferred to the collaboration feature: contribute-back — and its model is already decided: a collaborator's edits are OFFERED to the originator, who approves or rejects them (the same approve pattern as Q2).</p></li><li><p><strong>Q4 — Citations — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> Mandatory citations on every refreshed node; they cannot be turned off. Displayed as compact inline source references (a \"Sources\" affordance, not body-text clutter). Source URLs and metadata are stored on the node so they persist and travel with the outline.</p></li><li><p><strong>Q5 — Manual-Edit Conflict Handling — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> Auto-skip manually-edited nodes by default. The refresh dialog shows which nodes were skipped because the user had edited them, with a per-node explicit opt-in override. Requires tracking a \"user-edited\" flag per node.</p></li><li><p><strong>Q6 — Model Attribution — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> Surface model attribution on every refresh, attributing whichever model did the refresh (Claude, Gemini, or local), shown unobtrusively next to the citations (e.g., \"Refreshed with Claude · 4 sources\"). Pre-launch action item: verify the exact required wording and placement for Claude with Anthropic per their usage policy.</p></li><li><p><strong>Q7 — Node Update Behavior — CLOSED (decided 2026-05-15):</strong> Default = MERGE/AUGMENT — the AI revises the node in place: preserves still-accurate content, updates stale parts, and folds in genuinely new information; it does NOT discard the node and regenerate wholesale. An explicit 'Overwrite / regenerate from scratch' option is available in the refresh dialog for when the user wants a clean rewrite of a section. Both operate behind the Q2 preview/approve gate, with per-node granularity inherited from the existing preview UI.</p></li></ul><p><strong>Implementation implications (for the implement-LIVE-BOOKS task):</strong></p><ul><li><p>New per-node data: a user-edited flag, citation/source metadata, and model-used metadata.</p></li><li><p>New refresh dialog UI: a scope selector defaulting to the selected node plus its descendants; a preview/diff with per-node accept/reject; a skipped-edited-nodes list with per-node opt-in; and an optional auto-apply opt-in.</p></li><li><p>Refresh engine must support an in-place merge/augment mode (preserve+integrate) as the default, plus a full-regenerate mode as an explicit option; the preview must show whichever was applied.</p></li><li><p>Uses the existing AI provider abstraction plus web retrieval.</p></li><li><p>No sharing infrastructure required for v1.</p></li></ul>",
      "prefix": "16.1"
    },
    "unrealized-platform-gaps": {
      "id": "unrealized-platform-gaps",
      "name": "Platform Gaps",
      "parentId": "unrealized-todo-20260513",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Apple platforms first, but the other four targets in the Rosetta Stone need work before they can be claimed as supported.</strong></p><p></p><ul data-type=\"taskList\"><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Android Capacitor project scaffolding — not started. Capacitor is compatible by design but no Android project exists in the repo.</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Windows distributed build — electron-builder config exists, no distributed binary has been produced or tested</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Linux distributed build — electron-builder config exists, no distributed binary has been produced or tested</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>iOS multi-select audit — the Rosetta Stone explicitly marks multi-select as “needs audit” on iOS/Android. Confirm gesture, taps-to-select, and visual feedback work on a real iPhone.</p></div></li></ul><p></p><p><em>Note: iOS TestFlight upload itself is already tracked in the Session Log (May 8 entry) — deferred to office / fast internet — so it is not duplicated here.</em></p>",
      "prefix": "16.2"
    },
    "unrealized-mcp": {
      "id": "unrealized-mcp",
      "name": "MCP Server — Phases 2–4 + Test 8",
      "parentId": "unrealized-todo-20260513",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Status:</strong> MCP server exists in <em>mcp-server/</em> with Phase 1 (read-only tools) shipped. Phases 2–4 and the end-to-end Claude Desktop test are still unimplemented. See <em>IdiamPro-MCP-Plan.idm</em> for the full spec.</p><p></p><ul data-type=\"taskList\"><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>MCP Phase 2 — free CRUD tools (create / update / delete nodes and outlines)</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>MCP Phase 3 — premium AI / ingest tools (gated by subscription, behind paywall)</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>MCP Phase 4 — dual-licensing strategy (open-source free tools, commercial license for premium tools)</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Test 8 — Claude Desktop end-to-end run (connect the MCP server to Claude Desktop, exercise full tool surface against a real outline)</p></div></li></ul>",
      "prefix": "16.3"
    },
    "unrealized-group": {
      "id": "unrealized-group",
      "name": "Collaboration / Group Features — Design-Only",
      "parentId": "unrealized-todo-20260513",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Status:</strong> Everything in <em>IdiamPro - Group.idm</em> is design-only. No code has been written. This is a large body of work and likely a separate product surface from the solo-user experience.</p><p></p><ul data-type=\"taskList\"><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Electronic Brainstorming — multi-user simultaneous idea capture</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Voting — group decision-making on nodes / proposals</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Anonymous Contributions — hide attribution to reduce bias</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Collaborative Categorization — group-built taxonomies / tag systems</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Prioritization Tools — ranking, dot-voting, weighted scoring</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Yjs CRDT backend — real-time multi-user merge engine</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>WebSocket rooms — transport layer for live sessions</p></div></li></ul>",
      "prefix": "16.4"
    },
    "unrealized-external-deps": {
      "id": "unrealized-external-deps",
      "name": "External Dependencies (Waiting On)",
      "parentId": "unrealized-todo-20260513",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Items blocked on external responses or upstream decisions. Already partially tracked elsewhere — consolidated here so the dependency chain is visible in one place.</strong></p><p></p><ul data-type=\"taskList\"><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>4 enterprise API applications — Anthropic, Groq, OpenAI, Google. All submitted by 2026-05-08. Responses pending. (Detail in Section 15.)</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Managed API proxy — gated on the first enterprise agreement closing. (Detail in 15.5.)</p></div></li><li data-checked=\"false\" data-type=\"taskItem\"><label><input type=\"checkbox\"><span></span></label><div><p>Subscription billing backend — there is a code TODO in <em>src/contexts/ai-context.tsx</em> noting that localStorage plan loading is disabled until subscription billing is live. Re-enable when M3 ships.</p></div></li></ul>",
      "prefix": "16.5"
    },
    "session-2026-05-15": {
      "id": "session-2026-05-15",
      "name": "Thursday, May 15, 2026",
      "content": "<p><strong>Proactive outline updates this session:</strong></p><ul><li><p>Closed all 6 LIVE BOOKS design questions with the user; decisions recorded; LIVE BOOKS v1 scoped local-first with no collaboration dependency.</p></li><li><p>2026-05-15: Closed LIVE BOOKS Q7 (node-update behavior): default merge/augment, optional full overwrite — all 7 LIVE BOOKS design decisions now closed.</p></li><li><p>2026-05-15: Decided sharing roadmap: Level 1 (publish→link→personal-fork import) builds now; Level 2 contribute-back; Level 3 = modern GDSS in the GroupSystems lineage built natively on the structured outline (long-term target, design questions TBD).</p></li><li><p>2026-05-15: Decided: Level 3 GDSS collaboration is a separate B2B product with its own pricing (corporations/teams/institutions), distinct from consumer free/pro/premium tiers.</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Recorded flagship selling point: Multilingual Collaboration Board (multilingual teams collaborate each in their own language + foreign-language documents auto-integrated) — tied to Level 3 GDSS (#12) and language translation (#52).</p></li></ul>",
      "type": "text",
      "parentId": "session-actions-log",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "livebooks-sharing-roadmap-20260515": {
      "id": "livebooks-sharing-roadmap-20260515",
      "name": "Sharing Facility — Roadmap Decision (2026-05-15)",
      "content": "<p>Sharing facility roadmap decided 2026-05-15. THREE LEVELS. Level 1 (BUILD NOW): author publishes an outline snapshot to a hosted store → shareable link → recipient opens a web landing page, views it, 'Add to my outlines' imports it as their own independent personal-fork copy (reuses existing .idm import). One-way, snapshot-based, no live co-editing. Owner can re-publish (update snapshot) or revoke. Depends on the auth foundation (Clerk, env-gated, Phase 1 in progress) and a storage-backend choice (recommend simplest Vercel-native option, TBD). Level 2 (FOLLOW-ON): contribute-back — recipient's changes are offered to the originator who approves/rejects (model already decided in LIVE BOOKS Q3). Level 3 (LONG-TERM TARGET): full GDSS — see Decision B. Level 1 must be structured so Levels 2 and 3 are clean extensions.</p>",
      "type": "node",
      "parentId": "unrealized-livebooks",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "session-2026-05-17": {
      "id": "session-2026-05-17",
      "name": "Sunday, May 17, 2026",
      "content": "<p><strong>Proactive outline updates this session:</strong></p><ul><li><p>Shipped Auth Phase 2 billing scaffolding (env-gated) + LIVE BOOKS feature (generalized transform engine, 4-place docs); TEST EVERYTHING 38/38 clean in relocated repo; added automated LIVE BOOKS test (core surface runtime-proven; live-refresh round-trip residual tracked).</p></li><li><p>2026-05-17: Flagged May 19 Gemini keynote plan as the explicit next-up item in the launch dashboard.</p></li></ul>",
      "type": "text",
      "parentId": "session-actions-log",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "bringing-beta-testers-online": {
      "id": "bringing-beta-testers-online",
      "name": "Bringing beta testers Online",
      "parentId": "marketing-influencers",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "chapter",
      "content": "<p><strong>Last updated:</strong> 2026-06-03</p><p>This is the full, repeatable process for taking a person from \"I'd like to try IdiamPro\" to \"they have it installed and are sending you useful feedback.\" Run through this for each new tester. Once it's familiar, the per-tester time is about 5 minutes plus their install step.</p>\n\n<h3>Prerequisites (one-time setup — see the Launch Progress punch list for current status)</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Apple Developer Program active</strong> ($99/yr). Verify at appleid.apple.com → Account → Developer.</li>\n<li><strong>IdiamPro uploaded to App Store Connect.</strong> This is on your punch list — needs Xcode + certs + fast internet. Until it's uploaded, you cannot add beta testers at all. Order: open the iOS project in Xcode → Product → Archive → Distribute → App Store Connect.</li>\n<li><strong>Beta Test Information filled in</strong> (App Store Connect → IdiamPro → TestFlight → App Information): Beta App Description, Feedback Email (use your support email), Marketing URL, Privacy Policy URL. Apple requires these before external testing.</li>\n<li><strong>TestFlight group(s) created</strong> in the TestFlight tab — at minimum one Internal group and one External group.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Internal vs External — which to use</h3>\n<p><strong>Internal Testing</strong> (up to 100 testers): For your inner circle. No Apple review needed per build, so builds are available to testers within minutes of upload. But each tester must first be added to your Apple Developer team via App Store Connect → Users and Access. Use for: yourself on other devices, co-founders, close advisors who already have Apple Developer accounts.</p>\n<p><strong>External Testing</strong> (up to 10,000 testers): For everyone else. Just an email — no team membership needed. The first build of each external group gets Apple beta review (24-48 hours typically). Subsequent builds to the same group skip review unless the build introduces significant new features. Use for: friendly users, target customers, influencers, real beta testers.</p>\n<p><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Default to External for nearly everyone. Use Internal only for people who're already on your dev team.</p>\n\n<h3>The process — for each new tester</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Get info from the tester:</strong> their name + the email tied to their Apple ID (or that they can/will tie to one). If they don't have an Apple ID, send them apple.com → \"Create your Apple ID\" first; come back when done.</li>\n<li><strong>Decide group:</strong> Internal or External. Default External.</li>\n<li><strong>For Internal only — first add to team:</strong> App Store Connect → Users and Access → \"+\" → enter their Apple ID email + name → assign a role (Developer or App Manager works for testers) → Save. Apple emails them an invite to join your team. They must accept before you can add to a TestFlight Internal group.</li>\n<li><strong>Add to TestFlight group:</strong> App Store Connect → My Apps → IdiamPro → TestFlight tab → choose your Internal or External group → \"+\" or \"Add Testers\" → enter their email and name → Save.</li>\n<li><strong>Apple sends the invite automatically.</strong> Tester gets an email titled \"You're invited to test IdiamPro\" with a redemption link or code.</li>\n<li><strong>Tester's part — TestFlight install:</strong>\n  <ul>\n  <li>Open the invite email on their iPhone or iPad</li>\n  <li>Tap \"View in TestFlight\" or \"Start Testing\"</li>\n  <li>If they don't already have TestFlight: prompted to install it from App Store (free, official Apple app)</li>\n  <li>Open TestFlight → tap Accept → tap Install</li>\n  <li>IdiamPro appears on their home screen with a small orange dot indicating beta</li>\n  </ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Confirm install:</strong> App Store Connect → TestFlight → your group → testers table shows install status, session count, and time spent per tester. Refresh after a day to see who actually opened the app.</li>\n<li><strong>Send your welcome message</strong> (separately via email, not via TestFlight). See the template node 13.4 for tone. Should cover:\n  <ul>\n  <li>Thanks for joining the beta</li>\n  <li>What to focus on (specific feature areas, or \"use it however you naturally would\")</li>\n  <li>How to submit feedback — two paths: (a) TestFlight built-in: long-press app on home screen → \"Send Beta Feedback\"; (b) email your support address directly</li>\n  <li>Time commitment expectation (be explicit — \"spend 20-30 minutes over the next week if you can\")</li>\n  <li><strong>Confidentiality reminder:</strong> this is a pre-public build. Don't post screenshots publicly, don't share the TestFlight invite link, don't reveal features that aren't yet announced.</li>\n  <li>Direct line to you for serious issues (your personal email or phone, not just the support inbox)</li>\n  </ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h3>Tracking — keep it simple</h3>\n<p>Maintain a list (this outline, a spreadsheet, or a Notion page) with one row per tester:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Name</li>\n<li>Email</li>\n<li>Group (Internal / External)</li>\n<li>Date invited</li>\n<li>Date installed (if confirmed via App Store Connect)</li>\n<li>Feedback received: date + one-line summary</li>\n<li>Status (active / dormant / churned)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Important reminders</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Builds expire 90 days from upload.</strong> Plan to upload a refreshed build before the deadline if you want continuous testing without forcing testers to reinstall.</li>\n<li><strong>Tester can't see the invite?</strong> First: spam folder. Then: confirm the email is tied to an active Apple ID. Then: re-send via the testers table in App Store Connect.</li>\n<li><strong>Apple beta review for first external build takes 24-48 hours.</strong> Plan around this when adding the first wave.</li>\n<li><strong>The orange dot on the home screen icon</strong> is Apple's standard \"this is a beta\" indicator. Testers sometimes ask about it; it's normal and expected.</li>\n<li><strong>Feedback quality varies wildly.</strong> Some testers send detailed bug reports; many send \"looks good!\" Don't take silence personally. The signal you actually want is: did they keep using it? App Store Connect shows session counts — those tell you more than verbal feedback.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Immediate next step (as of 2026-06-03)</h3>\n<p>You can't run this process yet. The blocker is uploading the IdiamPro iOS build to App Store Connect (from Xcode, on your office machine with fast internet). That step is on the Launch Progress punch list. Once that's done, this entire process becomes a 5-minute-per-tester recurring task.</p>\n<p>When you have your first beta tester selected and the upload is done, work through steps 1-8 above and the tester will be live in TestFlight within an hour (Internal) or 24-48 hours (External, first build).</p>",
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": "13.5"
    },
    "video-generation-feasibility-2026-06-04": {
      "id": "video-generation-feasibility-2026-06-04",
      "name": "Video generation — feasibility + phased plan (post-launch)",
      "parentId": "root-bootstrap",
      "childrenIds": [
        "video-production-roadmap-hybrid-2026-06-11"
      ],
      "type": "chapter",
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": "17",
      "content": "<p><strong>Captured:</strong> 2026-06-04. <strong>Status:</strong> deferred to post-launch (v1.1+). <strong>Inspiration:</strong> Howard's question — \"just as we generate a podcast from outlines, could we also generate a YouTube video?\"</p>\n<p><strong>Short answer:</strong> Yes, absolutely feasible. But meaningfully harder than podcast generation. Recommendation: ship the slide-narration MVP as v1.1 once launch metrics show podcast usage validates the \"generate media from outlines\" pattern.</p><p><strong>Strategic value (Howard, 2026-06-04):</strong> beyond the feature itself, video generation is one of the strongest reasons a Free or Student user would upgrade to Pro — it's a tangible, high-perceived-value deliverable that's hard to get elsewhere for $9.99/mo. Plan and price accordingly: every Pro-vs-Free comparison page should highlight video generation prominently, and the upgrade prompt copy should call it out by name.</p>\n\n<h3>Why this idea fits IdiamPro's positioning</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><p>Outlines are inherently storyboard-able — every chapter is a scene, every sub-node is a beat. Video is the natural visual extension of the existing structure.</p></li>\n<li><p>The podcast feature established \"outline → audio media\" as a value prop. Video is the same prop with visuals — same workflow, broader output.</p></li>\n<li><p>Three concrete user segments: (1) creators turning research outlines into YouTube content, (2) educators turning lesson outlines into lecture videos, (3) sales/marketing teams turning pitch outlines into explainer videos. All three are paying-customer segments.</p></li>\n<li><p>Strong launch story: \"from outline to publishable video in one click.\"</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Why it's substantially harder than podcast</h3>\n<p>Podcast = generate script + TTS + serve MP3. Video adds three new pillars on top:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><p><strong>Visuals.</strong> The quality killer. Options range from low-effort (text slides) to high-cost (AI-generated video clips). Each tier has different cost + quality tradeoffs.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Audio-visual sync.</strong> Need word-level timestamps from the TTS so slide transitions land on the right beats. ElevenLabs supports this; OpenAI TTS does not. Pick TTS provider accordingly.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Composition / render pipeline.</strong> Combining audio + slides + transitions into an MP4. Two paths: (a) ffmpeg bundled with Electron (free, heavy install, no web/iOS support), (b) cloud render API like Creatomate, Shotstack, or JSON2Video ($0.10–$0.30 per minute of video, works on all platforms, simpler integration).</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Phased plan</h3>\n\n<h4>v1.1 MVP — \"Slide-narration video\"</h4>\n<p>The cheapest, fastest version that still feels professional. Ships in roughly 1–2 weeks of focused work after launch.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><p>Reuses script generation from the podcast pipeline (outline → narration script).</p></li>\n<li><p>Reuses TTS from the podcast pipeline (with the upgrade to word-timestamps for sync).</p></li>\n<li><p>Generates one slide per outline chapter/section, styled with IdiamPro branding. Title + 3–5 bullet points + a clean background.</p></li>\n<li><p>Stitches slides + audio with a cloud video API (recommend Creatomate for v1 — simplest JSON-template API, decent free tier for testing).</p></li>\n<li><p>Output: 720p MP4 downloadable. Optional: 1080p as a tier perk.</p></li>\n<li><p>Estimated unit cost: ~$0.20–$0.40 per 10-minute video (TTS + cloud render).</p></li>\n<li><p>UX: identical to podcast — \"Generate Video\" action, progress indicator, download when ready. Use the existing transform-engine pattern from LIVE BOOKS / Translate for the preview-and-approve cycle.</p></li>\n<li><p>Tier gate: Pro feature (same as podcast). 1 video = 1 generation against the Pro 1,000/month cap, OR a separate per-video credit counter if videos cost meaningfully more (likely yes — decide before shipping).</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>v1.2 — \"AI-enhanced video\"</h4>\n<p>Adds AI-generated visual assets so videos look less template-y.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><p>Per-scene AI image generation (DALL-E 3 or Stable Diffusion XL via Replicate). ~$0.04–$0.08 per image × ~30 images for a 10-minute video = ~$1.20–$2.40 per video on top of MVP costs.</p></li>\n<li><p>Optional: short AI-generated B-roll clips (Veo 2 or Sora when API-accessible, or Runway Gen-3 today). Significantly higher cost.</p></li>\n<li><p>Smart prompt construction: each scene's image prompt derived from the script + outline node content. Style controls (corporate, casual, educational) for consistency.</p></li>\n<li><p>New tier or per-video credit pricing required — unit cost ~10× the slide-narration MVP.</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>v2 — \"Studio tier\"</h4>\n<p>The premium offering for serious creators.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><p>Talking-head avatar option via HeyGen or Synthesia integration. User picks an avatar voice + appearance, system delivers a video with a presenter speaking the script.</p></li>\n<li><p>Direct YouTube upload via the YouTube Data API. OAuth flow, quota management. User clicks \"Publish to YouTube\" inside IdiamPro.</p></li>\n<li><p>Editorial controls: rearrange scenes, override AI-generated visuals, swap voice, adjust pacing — basic non-linear editing layered on the auto-generated baseline.</p></li>\n<li><p>Justifies a new top tier — Studio at $29.99 or $49.99/mo. Or per-video pricing for occasional users.</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Pricing model — open questions for post-launch decision</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><p>MVP slide-narration costs ~$0.30 to render. At Pro's $9.99/mo cap of 1,000 generations, generating 30 videos = $9 in render cost. Marginal. Roll into the existing Pro cap.</p></li>\n<li><p>AI-enhanced video costs ~$3 per video. Cannot be unlimited at $9.99/mo. Options: separate per-video credit pricing ($1–$2/video) OR a new Studio tier with bundled credits.</p></li>\n<li><p>Studio tier features (talking head, direct YouTube publish, editorial controls) justify $29.99–$49.99/mo on their own; the video credits become bundled with the tier.</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Technical architecture sketch</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><p><strong>Script generator</strong> — server action, reuses podcast pipeline. New input: target video length, target audience tone (corporate / casual / educational).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Scene splitter</strong> — converts script into ordered scenes. One scene per outline section by default; user can override.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Asset generator</strong> — slides (HTML→image via Puppeteer in a server function) OR AI images (Replicate API) OR AI video (Veo/Sora when available).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>TTS</strong> — ElevenLabs with timestamps. Generates audio per scene + word-level timing JSON.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Composer</strong> — sends scene-by-scene template (audio + visual + duration) to Creatomate, receives final MP4 URL.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Storage</strong> — render result hosted on Creatomate's CDN for download. Optional: copy to user's storage for retention.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Progress UI</strong> — render times can be 2–10 minutes. Show per-stage progress + estimated time remaining.</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Risks / things to watch</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><p><strong>Quality bar.</strong> A mediocre auto-video could hurt the brand more than help. Internal QA must be ruthless — show real outputs to real users before shipping.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Render time anxiety.</strong> 2–10 minutes feels long. Need clear progress UI + an email-when-done option.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Cost overruns.</strong> Heavy users could blow up render bills. Hard cap per tier + a cost dashboard for me to monitor.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Vendor lock-in.</strong> Creatomate vs. Shotstack vs. JSON2Video — pick after a side-by-side test against actual IdiamPro content during v1.1 build.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>iOS limitations.</strong> Even with cloud render, iOS Safari may have issues with large MP4 downloads. Test early. Possibly punt iOS to \"view-only\" with download via web.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>YouTube Data API quotas.</strong> Direct-upload (v2) needs OAuth and runs into daily quota limits. Manageable but adds support burden.</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>When to start</h3>\n<p><strong>Don't start before launch.</strong> Launch is 88% complete and the remaining P0 items (#6 onboarding emails, #7 Stripe web payment) need finishing without distraction. Adding video generation now would push the launch date by weeks for a feature that, until podcast adoption is validated, may not be the highest-ROI thing to build.</p>\n<p><strong>Trigger to start v1.1 MVP:</strong> when post-launch metrics show podcast generation usage above some threshold — suggested: >5% of Pro subscribers generate a podcast in their first 30 days. If podcast usage is hot, video is the obvious upsell. If podcast usage is cold, video would also be cold.</p>\n\n<h3>Decision needed before starting (when we get there)</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><p>Cloud render vendor: Creatomate vs. Shotstack vs. JSON2Video vs. build with ffmpeg.</p></li>\n<li><p>TTS provider lock-in for word-level timestamps: ElevenLabs vs. Azure vs. PlayHT.</p></li>\n<li><p>Pricing model for v1.1 MVP: bundled into Pro tier (acceptable cost) vs. credit pricing.</p></li>\n<li><p>Default video length / pacing — short-form (2–3 min) vs. long-form (8–15 min) as the default.</p></li>\n<li><p>Branding: IdiamPro watermark on free-tier videos? On all tiers?</p></li>\n</ol>"
    },
    "tech-stack-bootstrap-note-2026-06-06": {
      "id": "tech-stack-bootstrap-note-2026-06-06",
      "name": "Tech Stack Note — Why platform expansion is cheap (2026-06-06)",
      "content": "<p><strong>Why expanding to new platforms doesn't blow up the bootstrap budget.</strong></p><p>IdiamPro's stack is TypeScript end to end — React + Next.js, wrapped in Electron for desktop (Mac/Windows/Linux) and Capacitor for iOS. There's no Python anywhere. The same codebase ships to every platform.</p><p>Operational consequence for the bootstrap plan: adding Windows, Linux, or Android distribution later doesn't require a new engineering hire or a separate codebase — it's a build-config change against the existing TypeScript app. The cost of \"another platform\" is mostly store fees and signing certificates, not engineering headcount.</p><p></p><p><strong>Update-distribution operational note (2026-06-06):</strong></p><ul><li>Web and iOS updates already reach users with minimal friction (Vercel auto-deploy for web; Apple's auto-update flow for iOS).</li><li><strong>macOS desktop auto-updater — SHIPPED AT LAUNCH (2026-06-06).</strong> <code>electron-updater</code> integrated end-to-end. Mac users no longer have to manually download a fresh DMG: the app silently checks for updates 8s after launch + every 4 hours, downloads in the background, and surfaces a non-intrusive top-of-shell banner (Restart now / Later) when ready. Remaining externals are Howard's only: Apple Developer Application cert, electron-builder DMG signing flow, and the Vercel hosting upload of the signed DMG + <code>latest.yml</code> feed to <code>2ndbrainware.com/updates/mac/</code> (primary domain; secondbrainware.com becomes a redirect-only domain). The code-side integration does not block on those — it ships now and the production feed turns on the moment they land.</li><li>The same updater pattern covers Windows and Linux when those builds start shipping — no extra architectural work at that point.</li></ul><p><em>The full canonical description of the stack lives in the \"How it works\" outline under \"Technology Stack &amp; Platform Strategy.\" Do not duplicate it here — this section is operational only.</em></p>",
      "type": "standard",
      "parentId": "root-bootstrap",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "video-production-roadmap-hybrid-2026-06-11": {
      "id": "video-production-roadmap-hybrid-2026-06-11",
      "name": "Video Production Roadmap (Hybrid Pipeline)",
      "content": "<h3>Video Production Roadmap (Hybrid Pipeline)</h3><p>The 6-step workflow per video. Cross-reference: Marketing outline section 8 (Video Content → INTERNAL: Video Production Plan).</p><ol><li><strong>Script + storyboard + prompts</strong> — Claude Code writes the script, storyboard, AI-tool prompts, voiceover text.</li><li><strong>B-roll</strong> — Runway / MagicLight from Claude's prompts.</li><li><strong>Talking-head</strong> — HeyGen avatar or Howard records himself.</li><li><strong>In-app demo</strong> — real screen capture (Cmd+Shift+5 or ScreenFlow).</li><li><strong>Voiceover</strong> — ElevenLabs (or Howard records).</li><li><strong>Final edit</strong> — DaVinci Resolve / Descript stitches everything together with music and captions.</li></ol><p>Timeline: 60–90 sec polished video = ~2–4 hours once the pipeline is set up. 20-video library = ~6 weeks at 1/day.</p><p>Captured 2026-06-11.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "video-generation-feasibility-2026-06-04",
      "childrenIds": [
        "4be858c9-6ea0-4f78-8507-b32d18a9e46c"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": "17.1"
    },
    "video-ai-partnership-track-2026-06-11": {
      "id": "video-ai-partnership-track-2026-06-11",
      "name": "Video AI Partnership Track",
      "content": "<h3>Video AI Partnership Track</h3><p>Same playbook as the API provider partnerships. Targets in priority order: Runway, MagicLight, HeyGen, OpenAI Sora, Google Veo, Pika, Synthesia.</p><p>Partnership types: co-marketing, partner pricing for IdiamPro users, integration (embed APIs in-app), quarterly check-ins.</p><p>References memory: <code>project-ai-video-tool-partnerships</code>. Status tracking lives in the Operations outline (planned).</p><p>Captured 2026-06-11.</p>",
      "type": "node",
      "parentId": "marketing-influencers",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": "13.6"
    },
    "4be858c9-6ea0-4f78-8507-b32d18a9e46c": {
      "id": "4be858c9-6ea0-4f78-8507-b32d18a9e46c",
      "name": "Master video production plan (Marketing 8)",
      "content": "",
